I could show mercy if they were clean.
My district was stricken with famine and the plague.
A man was caught eating corpses and was hung as a warning.
At night his wife came and dug up his body, and she and her children ate it.
She deserved to be hanged as he was.
And the children?
-The children, too.
-Were they not clean?
There is no difference.
Then there would be no human beings left alive.
Life would become extinct.
Let it be extinct.
Only angels will remain.
No one has ever seen them.
And yet I hear their wings beating.
They are here with us.
They must be.
Otherwise we would live in darkness like dogs or wolves.
I'm scared of you, brother.
Why should only the virtuous die, of cold and hunger in their cells?
Death brings redemption from such a loneliness.
I carried this sand all the way from the Holy Land.
It's soaked with my brother's blood.
But why was it their blood?
The others live without faith, and breed like flies.
There are ever more of them!
I have deep respect for your long pilgrimage.
-But go home.
-When is the wedding?
Go back to your people.
There you'll find peace.
At least you'll stay clean.
Bees are like people.
They fear and sense disaster.
