Show him out!
- It will not take long, Regent.
How dare you!
Why did you come?
You have ordered the men to dig foundations for the new barn today.
It is not a good place, my lord.
Is that so? - Don't you remember what happened 5 years ago?
At that very place, your carman Daniel...
Fell into a pit dead drunk.
So?
- The pit wasn't there before.
I know this country.
And I know you, miller.
I wanted to...
...to have a clear conscience.
Your serfs seem quite bold, I dare say.
Regretfully, My Lord Bishop, that churl sits on a freehold farm.
You have lost all the same.
People say he is in consort with the devil.
When I was aspiring for the bishop's see, my competitor said the same about me.
Well! No ill feeling.
It doesn't seem to bother you.
Although it should!
- You have a parish priest.
Indeed!
A dimwit that believes in miracles.
You have gone too far, Regent.
You are talking about the spiritual shepherd of your subjects.
This man is their shepherd.
You can never burn him.
What do you mean by that?
Only the devil knows.
It all began almost a hundred years ago.
During the long wars with the Swedes.
My gamekeeper's great grandfather saw it all with his own eyes.
A mill stood on the same place as today.
Only its roof was thatched.
Back then, the miller's grandfather lived there.
Of the same miller you saw a short while ago.
After the Swedes had finally left, a mass for the miller's slain family was served.
And the place has been called the Burnt Mill ever since.
In short, whom fire leaves unharmed, dreads neither hell nor the Lord.
How came it?
Why didn't they burn in the fire?
- It was a miracle.
Light.
Light!
In the name of the Father and the Son and the Holy Spirit. Amen.
Hail Mary, full of grace, our Lord is with thee, blessed art thou among women, and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Holy Mary, mother of God, pray for us sinners now and in the hour of our death.
Amen.
Behold the handmaid of the Lord.
Be it done to me according to thy word.
Hail Mary, full of grace, our Lord is with thee blessed art thou among women, and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Holy Mary, mother of God, pray for us sinners now and in the hour of our death.
Amen.
Come to me.
Come.
Come, you silly.
Come, don't be afraid.
Let go. Let go!
The whole village is here.
Not to worry, they have other things on their mind.
Let go, Filip!
- Are my hands too cold?
Let go of me!
Who is it?
Come to the chapel tonight.
- I won't.
Will you come?
- No!
Quiet. Is something wrong?
We can stop if you wish.
- Jakub.
The fourth one.
- How comes?
It's the fourth bucket.
Go now! Next!
But it's the second one.
- Your buckets are twice as big.
The others have just the same.
You will come to work on Sunday.
- For a little water?
Be off, churl!
- You have no right to do that!
What right are you talking about?
The law doesn't impose corvee for water.
The miller told you that, didn't he?
Or did you read it?
Speak!
Help him!
Let him go!
Father...
Clemency behoves the suzerain.
And obedience the villein.
Go!
So you are the priest?
You are not quite how I imagined you.
His Excellency, the Bishop, made a certain promise regarding your...
He mentioned something about your...
- That is correct.
About me being of noble descent.
I beg your pardon.
I had no idea...
It is quite all right.
I truly hadn't the faintest idea, Monsignor Probus.
I am a mere chaplain here, Regent.
I have been informed of your troubles.
The bishop, however, certainly does not know what a disaster the Lord sent upon us.
As far as people remember, there has never been such a drought.
I have noticed.
Our well is the last one with water.
It has its advantages.
- I do not understand, Monsignor.
I am a chaplain, Regent.
And in a way, the drought is grist for the mill.
What's this supposed to mean?
I need someone dependable.
Praise the Lord!
Here's water for everyone!
That was a swell idea, son!
- And I don't even want you to drudge for me.
Come to the chapel tonight.
To the chapel? No.
Why not?
- Not there.
Back to work!
Back to work!
- Come to the lord's barn.
Back to work!
What did I tell you!
Get moving!
It counts for you too, doesn't it?
- What are you doing?
Don't you know how precious water is nowadays?
Is there any left?
Just a little, Father.
That's just what we needed.
I won't drink, Father.
It's good.
It should be, it's from the mill,
Father.
God bless you, son.
There's no need to frown.
A miller's shirt can hardly compete with a gamekeeper's coat.
And if she doesn't know, her parents will no doubt tell her.
She doesn't have any.
- That's even better.
In that case the suzerain will decide her matters.
We are here, Father.
A horrible abyss.
- People say, Father, that it is the gate to hell.
Give me a stone.
Be careful, Father.
There is no way forward or back for a living creature.
Is the mill far from here?
- It isn't, Father.
Come!
Welcome, Father.
I heard you coming.
I am getting to know my new parish and I would like to speak... with your father.
We are yeomen, Father.
Is your father here?
He's outside.
There's not much work in summer.
What a pity!
I wanted to take a look around.
I see you've heard our story.
I didn't come because of that.
I'm curious.
I hear water, yet I don't see it anywhere.
But it's dark there, Father.
Let's take the candle.
- Not this one!
This one is lit only when the miller passes away.
This is where it springs out.
And where does it go?
Nobody knows, Father.
Do you want me to turn on the millwheel?
There's is no need.
What's in here?
- A cellar.
Could I have a look?
Why are there so many candles everywhere?
We are the only mill where the water doesn't freeze.
And in winter, we grind flour overnight too.
I am glad
I could show you everything, Father.
Why?
- Because you may hear that the devil turns our millwheel.
We are lucky, Father.
Do you hear me, Father?
Father, the burnt miller!
The miller!
I'm curious to know what you are doing here.
Listen.
Halt!
Whoa, beasts!
Come on! Whoa!
Stop that witchcraft of yours, miller!
Idiot.
It sounded differently.
A hollow.
There must be more of them.
- That means...
That means...
Look.
Globeflower.
And it's growing on this dry land.
Why are you searching for water?
You have enough in your mill.
But the village has none, Father.
And our mill is too far.
That's very noble of you.
I've been searching all my life.
And learning as well.
Whether a rock yields water depends on the will of God.
Well, I'm not giving up hope.
You turn to the earth for help.
While l...
What's the matter?
What happened, Martina?
Did I hurt you in any way?
Say something.
I'm scared, Jan.
Martina...
I've heard strange things about your family again today.
About your father and...
- Martina, for God's sake!
It's nothing but old wives' tales.
You know who is spreading them and why.
- Shut your mouth!
I'm glad to see you admit it.
I've got nothing to say to you.
- But I've got plenty to say to you.
Let's go, Jan.
If you dare touch her one more time, you will have to deal with me.
You can't order me around!
And as far as she is concerned, others will decide about her.
Wait!
- Why such a hurry?
Get out of my way!
Why aren't you eating?
- I've always laughed at all the gossip, but last night, I started to care about what people say.
You will get used to it.
It's not me I'm worried about.
Is she afraid of us?
I don't mean just the silly tales.
This place really seems cursed.
Why don't you ever talk about it?
I don't.
- But why?
I am your son after all.
You will learn everything after I am gone.
From who?
Don't be so inquisitive.
I didn't ask you where you were all night, did l?
Lord, have mercy on us.
- Jesus Christ, have mercy on us.
Lord, have mercy on us.
Jesus Christ, hear our voices.
Jesus Christ, hear our prayer.
The Father in heaven.
- Have mercy on us.
The Son, saviour of the whole world.
- Have mercy on us.
The Holy Spirit.
- Have mercy on us.
The Holy Trinity: one God.
- Have mercy on us.
The Lord of heaven and earth.
- Have mercy on us.
The God in whom we live.
- Have mercy on us.
The God without whom we perish.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who sets boundaries to seas.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who measures riverbeds.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who fills springs with water.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who covers the sky with clouds.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who rules over rain and dew.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who sends rainfall and droughts.
- Have mercy on us.
The God to whom we fold our hands to pray. - Have mercy on us.
The God whose help we humbly ask.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who knows all our needs.
- Have mercy on us.
The God who cares for our wellbeing.
- Have mercy on us.
The God whose wisdom is impenetrable.
- Have mercy on us.
God, our Father.
- Have mercy on us.
Be merciful to us.
- Forgive us, Lord.
Be merciful to us.
- Hear our prayer, Lord.
From all evil.
- Save us, Lord.
From all sins.
- Save us, Lord.
From thine anger.
- Save us, Lord.
From unfavourable winds.
- Save us, Lord.
From burning heat.
- Save us, Lord.
From devastating drought.
- Save us, Lord.
From scarcity of our daily bread.
- Save us, Lord.
From the threat of poor crop.
- Save us, Lord.
From scarcity of water.
- Save us, Lord.
From early and eternal death.
- Save us, Lord.
We sinners.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Cover the sky with clouds.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Water the thirsty lands.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Fill the springs, brooks and rivers.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Bless and maintain our crop.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Show us thy mighty powers.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Turn our sorrow into happiness.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Open the fountains of thy mercy.
- Hear our prayer as we beseech you.
Lamb of God who takes away the sins of the world. - Forgive us, Lord.
Lamb of God who takes away the sins of the world. - Hear our prayer, Lord.
Lamb of God who takes away the sins of the world. - Have mercy on us.
Jesus Christ, hear our voices.
- Jesus Christ, hear our prayer.
Lord, have mercy on us.
- Jesus Christ, have mercy on us.
Lord, have mercy on us.
Our Father, who art in heaven, hallowed by thy name.
Thy kingdom come, thy will be done on earth as it is in heaven.
Give us this day our daily bread.
And forgive us our trespasses, as we forgive them that trespass against us.
And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil. Amen.
Hail Mary, full of grace, our Lord is with thee, blessed art thou among women, and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Holy Mary, mother of God, pray for us sinners now and in the hour of our death.
Amen.
Our Father, who art in heaven, hallowed by thy name.
Thy kingdom come, thy will be done on earth as it is in heaven.
Give us this day our daily bread.
And forgive us our trespasses, as we forgive them that trespass against us.
And lead us not into temptation, but deliver us from evil. Amen.
Hail Mary, full of grace, our Lord is with thee, blessed art thou among women, and blessed is the fruit of thy womb, Jesus.
Holy Mary, mother of God, pray for us sinners now and in the hour of our death.
Amen.
I will throw him into prison!
For what crime?
For finding water?
The court will deal with him.
- What can the court prove to him?
What? Anything. Interrupting a religious ceremony, for example.
Nonsense. The people came to him.
Being in consort with the devil then!
After all, that is within your competence, isn't it?
And can you or I for that matter say with certainty that he didn't find the spring out of God's will?
You will pay dearly for this, Jan.
Is the village feast today?
- A feast?
The miller gave water to the people, and the regent has to give them beer.
That boaster ordered to roll out five barrels on the threshing-floor.
The threshing-floor?
- Right there.
They told the people it's to celebrate the new barn.
Very clever of them indeed.
What have you got there? Show me.
The reverend is here.
- You are here too.
And the regent.
- And me.
I'm scared.
- I love you.
Jan...
The regent will never consent to it.
Let's get out of here.
Have you finished dancing?
- Leave us alone.
Do you want to spoil everything?
Wait for me here.
Suddenly, there's plenty of water.
And beer.
A solo!
- You can spare yourself the trouble!
Play!
You didn't get enough last time, did you?
Very well, I can add some more.
Get the catchpole!
Wait!
Let them be!
Put the knives away!
Throw the knife away.
And you all should listen!
You shouldn't be dancing here.
- How dare you?
Go back to your mill!
I'm the one who is paying for all this!
Don't forget that I've always given you good advice.
I'm the one who gives orders around here!
Dance.
Music!
Don't you hear?
Why are you standing here like idiots?!
Dance!
A step dance!
The feast was a smart idea indeed!
My carriage!
Get the miller.
You seem to forget I am a free man.
And you forget you are to blame for all those souls buried under!
I warned you all in time.
How could you know beforehand?
The earth talks.
Do you hear voices from the earth?
I don't understand.
You have just said so yourself.
All my life, I walk about and observe.
What has it got to do with the barn?
You built the barn on a site where snow hasn't lasted for many winters.
What does it mean?
Because heat has been rising from crevices up to the surface.
Heat? From frozen earth?
Down below the earth never freezes.
Do you know where the heat down below comes from?
Do you know the Bible?
I do.
And do you know what the Bible says about hellfire?
I am a good Christian, Father.
If you recall our first encounter, that is how I speak with the earth.
And it told me where to find water then.
And if you recall what I told you then,
I wish to add only this.
Only four-legged cattle walk with their heads lowered to the ground.
While a man created in the image of God
Iooks up to the heavens with confidence.
And there, he finds answers to everything.
But the earth gives us water and bread.
Bread and water are God's gifts that we beg from the Lord day by day.
You are a heretic.
Perhaps you do not know how perilous are the paths that have lead you astray.
You listen to the voices of nature.
The more insinuating they are the less your ears are able to hear the only voice you should listen to.
And who do you think urges you not to listen to the Lord?
I see you wish to object that you do good for the people.
But don't you know that the Devil lures people namely by what gives them pleasure?
Father, I am listening to you attentively.
Hold your tongue!
- However, in my conscience
I find no wrongdoing.
- What impenitence!
You have criminated yourself!
You are a wise man, miller.
I would feel great pity if you were to account for your deeds to the Holy lnquisition.
I will lend you a helping hand.
I expect to see you at my Sunday homily.
You may go now.
What's this supposed to mean!
Why did you let him go?
I've had enough of your ideas!
Why make such a fuss?
I'll throw him into prison!
And he will become a martyr.
The people will rid the Lord's garden of poisonous weed themselves.
Don't you understand?
After the procession and all that happened, he still may come.
The regent will never give his consent.
Hail Mary, full of grace...
Martina.
A this very place I am telling you that I will never give you up.
My father and me, we have a clear conscience. Nobody can harm us!
Martina?
Father...
Where did you find it?
I take my herd here to drink every morning.
But how did his hat get here?
Well, your father used to come here too.
Sometimes down here and other times up there.
What's up there?
He watched the pools down there, how the water keeps rising and dropping.
Green wreath of nine flowers woven, show me who my husband will be.
This is no evidence.
He hasn't been home for two nights.
He can't be alive.
- Now that's odd.
Particularly today when he was to come to the homily.
You knew, didn't you?
I didn't.
I reminded him to come and what happened?
His son came instead.
Do you mean to say he drowned in brook so shallow it hardly reaches one's toes?
Not in the brook, Father.
- In that case tell me the truth!
Where is he?
He either ran away or he is hiding.
You know the truth.
And you are lying through your teeth.
I don't understand at all.
You people from the mill when you do not want to, you do not understand at all.
Like father like son.
Father, for goodness' sake, what are you saying? - Go!
And don't come back unless remorse makes you fall on your knees and confess.
This way!
And there you will find an answer.
I shall now remove the blinders from your eyes and you shall see.
If your house or your house or your house burnt down, which one of you would walk out of the fire and ashes unharmed?
Which one of you would make water spring out of dry land when the Lord turned his face from us for so long?
Who made the earth open under your feet when you were rejoicing at your suzerain's kindness?
And whom am I missing on these sacred grounds despite urging him to come?
You, who are reading these words, are standing at a place...
...That has always protected us from war, plague, and even fire.
Safeguard this secret and search for a way out.
In front of you, you see three paths.
The first leads towards a light, yet it ends at the bottom of an abyss.
The second is the path of water and no one has ever reached its end.
The third, marked by a cross, is forbidden.
On this path, every step or mere sound of one's voice kills.
On the Friday before midsummer night when the barn sank into the ground, the water never being so low...
...As far as remembrance reaches. I set out to search for an exit on a raft.
Obeying the written word.
Obeying the written word.
Father.
Father!
Father!!!
Therefore, this man entangled in the net of dark powers dares not come and stand before the face of God.
I can see that in just wrath, you ask yourselves:
Where can we find the man you speak of?
And I ask you:
Where does a wild beast hide from hunters and their dogs?
Into its den. There you must go!
There you shall find him.
Let the hammer of your wrath strike the originator of evil there.
Should the hammer fail to strike in time, your souls shall forever be entangled in his nets, where in horrible suffering, they shall vainly seek redemption.
You must make haste!
Driven by the word of God, you must hurry to the mill and eradicate that den of evil!
And whatever you do above that, may you be aided the Father, the Son, and the Holy Spirit.
Amen.
My shoes!
If only you had told me what you wanted to do...
Until I have that old mole in my hand...
Everyone went home!
Until I get him on his knees,
I have nothing to explain.
Why are you standing there like that?!
You could have spared us the disgrace.
I'll get him!
My horse!
I guarantee you it!
Jan!
We've come to end it.
Where is your father?
Speak!
Don't go there, Father.
Miller!
Filip!
I warn you!
Go! Quick!
Shoot!
- Don't shoot!!!
Good Lord, Jan!
Jan...
Jan.
The End
CHUSHINGURA
Produced by SANEZUMI FUJIMOTO,
TOMOYUKI TANAKA & HIROSHI INAGAKI
Screenplay by TOSHIO YASUMI
Photography by KAZUO YAMADA
Art direction by KISAKU ITO
Music by AKIRA IFUKUBE
Sound recording by YOSHIO NISHIKAWA
Lighting by MASASHICHI KOJIMA
CAST
KOSHIRO MATSUMOTO as Kuranosuke Oishi
YUZO KAYAMA as Takuminokami Asano
TATSUYA MIHASHI as Yasubei Horibe
TAKASHI SHIMURA as Hyobu Chisaka
KEIJU KOBAYASHI as Awajinokami Wakisaka
RYO IKEBE as Chikara Tsuchiya
DAISUKE KATO
FRANKIE SAKAI
AKIRA TAKARADA
SEIZABURO KAWAZU
SOMEGORO ICHIKAWA
MANNOSUKE NAKAMURA
SETSUKO HARA as Riku Oishi
YOKO TSUKASA as Aguri Asano
MICHIYO ARATAMA
REIKO DAN
KEIKO AWAJI
MITSUKO KUSABUE
SADAKO SAWAMURA
CHIEKO NAKAKITA
HISAYA MORISHIGE as Hanbei
CHUSHA ICHIKAWA as Kozukenosuke Kira
TOSHIRO MIFUNE as Gemba Tawaraboshi
Directed by HIROSHI INAGAKI
PART I: BLOSSOMS
March 1701
Every spring the Shogun sends greetings to the Emperor in Kyoto.
In reply the Emperor sends envoys to the Shogun's castle in Edo.
OKITSU
Quiet! Be quiet.
The envoys are leaving.
Show your respect.
We pray for your success.
We await your speedy return.
Such a strain having nobles here.
Yes, and no tips. A loss for us.
Imperial envoys. Too bad.
They're assigned to our inn.
Don't take it out on your clothes.
Fold them up.
Yes, yes. Too bad being an adopted son-in-law.
What's that?
Talking to myself.
Master of this inn, but without an heir I'm nothing.
Complaining?
Because I'm master of this inn great men talk to me...
I hear the latest news. I guess it depends how you look at it.
Master, a crowd wants the bath water the nobles used.
To drink?
No, to wash themselves.
They believe it prevents illness.
Give it to them.
And get me a masseur.
My shoulders are so sore.
People see nobles as gods, but in reality...
In reality they're broke.
Say, did you lend him money?
Look.
What's this?
For the loan I gave him.
A terrible hand.
EDO
Make way!
The Shogun's dog.
The August Dog is passing!
RESCUE STRAYS.
HARM TO DOGS PUNISHABLE BY DEATH.
You are the Shogun's favorite.
My gift may not be worthy of you.
It is small, but a rare one from a foreign land.
With this I feel I hold the power over the world in my hands.
I am glad it has found favor in your eyes, my lord.
The imperial envoys arrive soon.
All is ready to welcome them.
I can rest easy with you in charge, Kira.
Have Asano and Date sent greetings?
Yes, two bolts of silk from Date.
Dried bonito, I think, from Asano.
What? Asano is now in charge of
Reception. Only bonito from him?
But surely to you, as Grand Master of Ceremonies, he's been generous?
No, I've received nothing from him.
How strange.
A post like Reception is the key to a lord's success.
Yes.
It's how we recognize his ability.
Especially Asano.
His vast estates have grown; he's added salt farms. He's very rich.
Yes, yes, quite so.
You've also started salt farms?
Ours can't be compared with his.
So recently I sent most politely to request his help.
But he flatly refused.
Refused?
He said it was the former lord's secret formula.
So he couldn't tell even me.
And after I had sent gifts, too.
Now he needs you to help him.
Even the score.
He was free to refuse me, but it is my official duty to teach him.
There are many ways to teach.
Make sure he learns his lesson.
Time to go to the Castle, my lord.
At this hour?
Actually, I'm going to bring the Shogun here.
You see, he visits me sometimes.
For a reason.
Feast your eyes.
Truly delightful.
I've kept you waiting.
I'm on my way. What fun!
The Shogun loves both learning and ladies.
What he wants, he is determined to get.
Our ranks differ, but we are alike.
Without a desire for money and women, life has no value.
With lust and greed as my values,
I intend to live a long life.
Lord Yanagisawa even offered his own wife to the Shogun.
She agreed to it.
That is how he rose to his post.
Now there is nothing he cannot do.
Tomi, are you listening?
Please live a long and greedy life.
What?
Our son has been adopted by the mighty Uesugi Clan.
You have become
Grand Master of Ceremonies.
You are related to Lord Yanagisawa.
What more could you want?
I don't understand.
Why be satisfied with that?
I'm only getting started.
Pardon.
Tachu?
There was a messenger from Date.
Again?
And then one came from Asano.
Oh? What did he bring? Where is it?
Is this all the head of Reception sends me?
Tachu, Lord Date is only assisting
Lord Asano...
Yet he sends this fine Kaga silk...
Two boxes of a hundred gold pieces, and paintings by Shinyu Kano.
Asano is mocking me!
That's all I can think.
So it seems.
Tachu, when I sent you to ask about the salt farms...
We did our utmost – a European vase and two hundred gold pieces.
But he returned them.
And now, when he needs my advice, he sends one paltry roll of silk.
Chamberlain.
Gengoemon, you're so rushed.
I just heard that we sent Lord Kira much less than Date did.
Yes, I've heard.
Do something!
Fujii is with our lord about it.
A word, my lord.
Lord Date gave Kira...
Date has his way, I have mine.
But...
I don't like bribery. I hate it!
It's the cause of corruption in the government, isn't it?
As long as he teaches me...
I will honor Lord Kira, and treat him with due respect.
Thank you for your concern.
But I will do as I see fit.
Have you been here long?
A little while.
You always stop when you see me.
Tomorrow I must leave for Denso Mansion.
Until the envoys go back?
Yes, we must converse with them at night as well.
It's my duty and can't be helped.
A brief separation.
We can't even talk to each other.
Don't say such sad things.
Play the koto for me every day at this time.
I know I'll hear it wherever I am.
I will, with all my heart.
Please carry out your duty safely.
Yes. Kuranosuke wrote me a letter from home.
He too is concerned.
With his letter and your music,
I'll do well at my duties.
What? Asano's chronic illness has flared up?
He knew I was coming to inspect.
Yes, but suddenly...
Suddenly what? He didn't want to see me, so he is ill?
Of course not.
Can he carry out his duties?
I feel better.
Lady Asano's medicine helped.
Tell Lord Kira I will join him.
Lord Asano, no one can take your place in this important role.
Are you aware of that?
I had a sudden attack today.
That is no excuse.
To fall ill at such a time is a grave error. It is negligence.
Forgive me.
That was my official opinion.
But I am here unofficially today.
Take good care of yourself.
I feel better now.
Thanks to the medicine from your lovely wife?
Show me around then.
Everything seems in order.
A gorgeous screen by Yusho.
Worthy of your famous clan.
Yes, even I, Grand Master of Ceremonies, find no fault here.
I am unworthy of your praise.
Please tell me where I may be lacking in the future.
Very well, I will teach you some of what I know.
Yes, I humbly ask you.
In a position of this kind, gifts are of the utmost importance.
Head of Reception means head of gift-giving. Understand?
Answer me if you do.
Yes.
It is crucial to be generous to those you meet along the way.
The word will spread, you will be well liked, your duties will ease.
It's expensive, but it leads to success if you are careful.
The more generous you are, the better the results.
Understand?
What is this, Lord Asano?
Old mats in the room where you will receive imperial envoys?
Is this fulfilling your duties?
I have apprised you fully of all the requirements.
Old mats will not do!
But when I asked the other day, you said they needn't be changed.
I said that?
You are joking.
No. You said it.
An old man's memory slip?
Not in something so important.
Change them.
But there's no time to change five hundred mats now.
Still, I hear you are rich.
Maybe you can if you pay enough.
But there is a way not to have to waste so much money.
If you used your money wisely...
Understand?
Anyway, this won't do.
My lord, it sounds as if Kira will overlook the mats if we pay him.
But you know the Kemmu Code expressly forbids bribery.
It's supposed to stop corruption in the government.
Kira is easy to bribe, but my integrity won't allow it.
But in such an emergency...
Your lord is an obstinate man.
Indulge my pride.
My lord, please let me handle the changing of the mats.
Gengo, can it be done?
If our clan's honor is at stake.
You make it sound easy.
But five hundred mats by morning?
I'll do it if I have to enlist every matmaker in all Edo.
Gengo, thank you.
Pardon.
I am Takebayashi, vassal of Asano.
Are you matmakers?
No? I'm sorry.
We're matmakers.
Matmakers? Keep calm.
Refuse and you're dead.
Refuse what?
Oh, yes. Keep calm!
I am Takebayashi. My life depends on the favor I have to ask you.
I understand. But to send over all my hands on such short notice...
But I am Gengo Otaka humbling myself before you. I beg you.
I'm sorry, but your humility is none of my affair.
I see. It can't be helped.
I don't understand what...
What are you doing?
Committing harakiri.
What? Not here, please!
So, you'll help us?
This is unfair.
Our clan's honor is at stake.
We won't make it at this rate.
Too slow. Too slow!
Can't you do it faster?
What's happened to Yasubei Horibe?
He remembered another big matmaker and went for him.
Must be Otokichi. A drunk.
Yasubei the drinker going after a drunken matmaker.
Another round.
Another big one!
Nice cheery voice. And orders a big one instead of singles.
You understand drinkers.
Isn't that right, neighbor?
You seem like a strong drinker.
"Seem" is not the word.
A bottomless pit. Never full.
My kind of man.
And you?
Never lost a drinking match, so I never have to pay.
I like that. Shall we?
I'll have to make you pay.
A barrel of sake here.
Otokichi, at last I found you.
Horibe, you're just in time for our drinking match.
Not now, please. I need your help.
On my honor as a man of Edo,
I'll help after this match.
No, come with me now.
No you don't.
We're about to drink our way to fast friendship.
You can't take my drinking partner.
I'm very sorry, but...
Your name, sir!
I am Gemba Tawaraboshi, masterless samurai...
Teacher of the Hozoin lance.
Will you finish by dawn?
Please. Leave mats to matmakers.
But I'm worried.
Worry about Horibe. He took my place against a strong adversary.
Dawn already.
One more drinking spot.
I'm not done in yet.
I'll win. You can't get me drunk.
There must be some reason I can't.
Could be.
Hard work serving a lord.
But leave mats to matmakers.
We did it. All finished.
All done.
Did we do it?
Mats as far as the eye can see.
We did it. I'm so glad.
Please bear with the rest and complete your duties, my lord.
Yes. You have upheld our name.
I can't thank you enough.
Please instruct me...
Do I receive the envoys at the top...
Or at the bottom of the steps?
Are the envoys to be greeted at the top steps or the bottom?
Once more.
Do I receive the envoys at the...
Why are you asking this so late?
Forgive me. Please instruct me.
Do as you please.
You dislike receiving my advice.
I have no answer for you.
Lord Asano.
I am sorry for you.
Lord Wakisaka.
I heard. Listen.
Any mistake you make would reflect on Kira. He'll tell you.
Be calm and composed when he does.
Thank you.
Your duties end tomorrow.
Until then close your eyes, stop up your ears and play dumb.
Play dumb?
The smallest upset could make your vassals homeless.
Please be cautious, Lord Asano.
Lord Asano, wrong place.
Get to your place!
Quickly! Facing Lord Date.
MARCH 14. THE SHOGUN ENTERTAINS
THE ENVOYS WITH A NOH PLAY.
Oh, I'm so sleepy.
What if we doze off at the play?
Then I'll do this.
An hour till the ceremony.
Please take your ease.
You understand?
You're late, Lord Asano.
I'm sorry.
I've studied this.
Lord Date, are the elders' instructions clear to you?
Make no mistakes.
Lord Kira, may I see that?
Lord Kira!
Since you don't like instructions,
Lord Asano, you needn't see it.
Then I cannot carry out my duties.
Please let me see it.
If I fail, I will be punished.
Unless I see the instructions,
I won't know...
Lord Kira!
Lord Asano.
It wasn't instructions.
It was only fire warnings and such.
But Lord Date...
Lord Kira is just being unpleasant.
Yes, unpleasant. Why only to me, day after day?
Come, it's almost time to meet the envoys.
One moment, Lord Date.
Lord Kira.
Lord Asano.
Lady Keishoin wishes to thank the envoys.
Please inform me when the ceremony ends.
Most certainly.
Oh, if you have a request, please ask me.
He knows nothing.
Lord Kira!
What do you want?
Please show me the instructions.
How tiresome. I said no.
Why not?
What a face. You'll be late meeting the envoys.
What are you doing? Let go!
Asano!
Watch yourself.
This is the Shogun's Castle.
Draw your sword here and your clan is doomed. You know that?
What...what are you doing?
Apologizing? Then I'll listen.
I lost my temper. I was rude.
Please forgive me.
You admit you acted like a country lord, you backwoods baron!
You don't like being called that?
You're ignorant, yet you scowl.
I can't stand the sight of you!
Kira, you...
Have mercy!
Remember where you are!
One more stab!
You're inside the Castle.
Your clan will be ruined. Calm down!
Lord Asano drew his sword!
A doctor! Lord Kira is injured!
Wretch!
Defiling my crest with blood!
I beg...I beg your pardon.
Closer!
Where are the envoys?
Luckily, they didn't hear.
I see.
Everything went as planned.
But the Elders are meeting now.
Why? The rules are clear.
Keep to the rules!
Calm down. Calm down!
The trouble is between Lord Kira and Lord Asano. No one else.
We are to investigate the motives behind this incident.
I will now question you formally.
When you wounded Lord Kira you were of course mentally deranged?
No, I was not.
If you were, you will be absolved of any crime.
You were deranged, were you not?
Not at all.
I regret with all my heart that I drew my sword in the Castle.
Please punish me.
You must have had a reason, and a wish to explain.
Do not hesitate to tell us.
I forbid him to explain.
Why? For what reason?
We did not come to hear excuses.
But, Lord Kondo...
If he was not mentally deranged, he is a criminal.
Our responsibility ends there.
Lord Asano...
I am sorry. Sorry only that Kira escaped.
Sister!
I have just heard.
How could he do such a thing?
The Asano Clan is doomed.
As his brother, I'll suffer too.
Our parents back in Hiroshima, and your parents too...
Up until this moment, I was happy.
But what my brother has done makes me bitter.
Lord Daigaku, will Lord Kira live?
I don't know.
What will they do to Lord Asano?
I have heard nothing yet.
I must know as soon as possible.
Lord Daigaku, have pity.
Pardon.
A messenger reports that our lord is in Lord Tamura's custody.
Lord Date.
You must feel relieved that your duties are over.
Yes, but I am disturbed over that unexpected incident.
Have you heard about Kira?
No, not yet.
They let him go home without a reprimand, to see to his wounds.
Lord Date, do you think it's fair?
I do not.
What about Lord Asano?
He wasn't allowed a word in his own defense.
They turned him over to Lord Tamura with orders to commit harakiri.
Late cherry blossoms, Lord Asano.
Especially lovely when they fall.
Soon the moon will rise.
Farewell on such a spring evening must be painful.
Isn't it, Lord Asano?
Tell me if you have any messages for your clan at home.
I have nothing to say.
But my people will wonder when they hear of this day.
Enough talk. All is prepared.
"Sadder than blossoms swept off by the wind...
"A life torn away in the fullness of spring."
I'm afraid. So afraid.
But the injury is so slight.
Fortunately.
But he is of advanced age.
Anything could happen.
Hyobu, I married into the Uesugi family.
But I will risk my new riches to save my father.
Let me be a dutiful son no matter what happens.
Tsunanori. Tsunanori!
Help me.
I haven't had my fill of wealth or women yet.
And, thankfully, no one has censured me.
I want to live much longer.
I'll do anything for it.
If I'm called a coward,
I'm proud to be one.
Help me. Help me.
I'm counting on you.
MARCH 15, 1701
COURIERS SPEED FROM EDO TO
LORD ASANO'S CASTLE
They're coming!
MARCH 16
MARCH 17
MARCH 18
Osei! Osei!
Take care of her! I am Sampei
Kayano of Lord Asano's clan.
We are on an emergency errand.
Forgive us! Forgive us!
THE ASANO CLAN CASTLE IN AKO
Father.
Everyone here?
How is the town?
Very quiet.
Wondering whether you will fight or surrender the castle.
We must decide that now.
I had hoped to live out my days uneventfully...
A useless soldier in peacetime.
Quiet, please!
The time for debate is over.
Let me sum up the arguments.
The choice is either to fight or to try to rebuild our clan.
That has been decided.
Oh? Which?
Our lives belong to our late lord.
We can't surrender the castle.
We've decided to die fighting.
You agree to that?
Of course.
All agreed?
Anyone with other ideas, step out.
No one?
Okano.
We are ready to die.
But has Kira died of the wound our lord inflicted?
If so, we have no excuse for anger.
Your ideas would change too.
Is he dead, Chamberlain Ono?
No, I think it's only a rumor.
Have you become reluctant to die?
What? I am Kurobei Ono, samurai.
I have given my word.
I would like your advice.
Yes, ask me.
The problem is...
I am responsible for the treasury.
We still have about 7,000 gold pieces left.
But our clan has issued 12,000 gold pieces in paper currency.
We are 5,000 short.
But we have given loans, and there is money we have not collected yet.
If we collect, we will cover it.
I'm relieved to hear that.
It doesn't matter to us, since we are going to fight and die.
But our paper money is used by merchants, fishermen and farmers.
It will disgrace our dead lord if we don't redeem it.
Quite true.
I would like permission to collect loans and taxes.
I want to do this before we fight.
Yes. Please hurry.
Lord Wakisaka is on his way to
Takatori Pass with 3,000 men.
He will take over our castle.
Please redeem the currency before that happens.
THE ARMY OF LORD WAKISAKA
Say, girls.
A real bargain.
Who cares? I'm clearing out.
Me too. Armies are coming from all over to surround Ako.
You should run too!
I believe only those loyal to our clan are here.
I wish to tell you my intentions.
Isn't our plan clear already?
Don't we die defending the castle?
My thinking has changed somewhat.
It's easy enough to die fighting.
But we have a larger responsibility as vassals of Asano.
What?
What happened was our lord's fault.
So our task is to restore the Asano Clan.
We must entreat the Shogun to let
Lord Daigaku succeed our lord.
I believe this must be our course of action. Do you all agree?
No. That would be a betrayal of our loyalty.
Chamberlain.
Remember our lord's last words?
He said his people would wonder when they heard of his death.
Why should we bow to injustice?
I understand. But I won't change my mind.
Isn't that Kazuemon Fuwa?
Kazuemon!
Kazuemon Fuwa!
Terrible, isn't it?
We've just returned from Edo.
Then you haven't heard they're going to die defending the castle?
It's been decided?
I'm just a masterless samurai now.
But I rushed over to defend the walls, at least, for my dead lord.
Look. I'm poor, but I still have my armor, and my lance isn't rusty.
How dare Ono run off with the clan treasury!
I suspected him, but chose to hope.
I was too trusting.
From now on I'll doubt everyone.
Emoshichi Yato is outside and wishes to see you.
I can't.
I told him that.
Give my regards and send him away.
What about the paper money?
The farmers have let us redeem it at only 60% of face value.
Many of them are more loyal than samurai.
Anything left for vassals?
If we don't fight we can divide our reserve of war funds.
Still here?
He won't leave till he sees you.
The chamberlain is busy, so tell me what you want.
I am Emoshichi, son of Chosuke, the bookkeeper.
Father is ill.
He is unable to present himself to show his loyalty. He suffers.
So, inexperienced as I am,
I came to take his place.
I understand. But you are not of age.
Stay home and be a good son.
Father's rank is low. Is that why?
No, it isn't.
But Matsunojo's under age.
He is Chamberlain Oishi's son.
Loyalty is loyalty, chamberlain's son or bookkeeper's.
I should have been born a chamberlain's son too.
With so many opinions we can't resolve this.
So if you are throwing in your lot with me...
Sign your name in blood.
Proceed regardless of your rank.
Oishi says they'll surrender, but they're reinforcing the castle.
So it's war?
We are surrendering, but we must repair unsightly damage.
Only 61signatures.
It's a hard thing to ask.
In desperate times, it's every man for himself.
Oishi got men to sign in blood.
What for? He's surrendering.
Maybe to calm the hot-heads.
It may be a trick. Go back to Edo and report to Chamberlain Chisaka.
Traitors!
Lord Uesugi's spies. That's who spread rumors of Kira's death.
Now we know Kira is still alive.
How?
Hyobu Chisaka is Lord Uesugi's famous chamberlain.
He's spying to see if we seek revenge.
Horibe, don't tell this to anyone.
Keep it your secret.
Hurry to Edo. Find out what Kira and Lord Uesugi are up to.
Yes, without fail.
LORD WAKISAKA'S CAMP
I think Ako will fight.
I can't believe they'll surrender tomorrow.
Please look.
Seems to be more than paper.
Paper holds the castle's history.
Vast amounts of paper.
Now I can surrender it with an easy mind.
I am Chamberlain Kuranosuke Oishi.
I respectfully surrender the castle.
I am Lord Wakisaka, appointed to take charge.
I will guide you, my lord.
I've heard you're a very able man.
The care you have taken in handing over this castle impresses me.
I was prepared for battle.
But it enhances my reputation to be able to avoid it.
I owe it to you.
You are kind.
But you must have a reason for handing it over so readily.
Tell me. I'll keep your secret.
There is none.
Those were my orders.
A battle might have spilled innocent blood.
Please, tell me your real intent.
I was your lord's friend in Edo.
I know that from his letters.
Lord Asano broke the Shogun's rules but he upheld the samurai code.
He risked his clan to stop corruption.
Please don't speak of that.
My late lord was responsible for what happened.
As his vassals, we plan to appeal to the Shogun to restore his clan.
We have sworn our allegiance.
Please help us by adding your entreaty to ours.
A vassal's way to repay his lord?
Yes.
Truly?
My lord left a last poem.
"Sadder than blossoms swept off by the wind...
"A life torn away in the fullness of spring."
Was he sad to die young, or is his poem about his resentment?
No, it shows his deep concern for his vassals.
I'm sorry.
They surrendered the castle to set up Lord Daigaku.
What about Oishi?
He's moved to Yamashina.
Thank you.
Go soon and check up on Oishi.
Restoring the clan?
Do you believe that, Ikkaku?
Revenge.
Yes, the real reason Oishi gave up the castle was to get Kira's head.
I'm glad to see you well, my lord.
Yes, I hope to live to a hundred.
The reason I studied to become
Grand Master of Ceremonies...
Was to avoid the samurai duty to die at the slightest provocation.
Samurai all look very stupid to me.
I too am a samurai.
Well, there are different kinds of samurai.
I depend on you, Hyobu, to protect me from Asano's stupid samurai.
My lord has ordered me to do so.
My son, who is now heir to the Uesugi clan, is very loyal to me.
But my wife is a heartless woman.
Afraid I'd be criticized, she went back to her parents.
And left me all alone.
Hyobu, I'm counting on you.
I'm afraid. You must help me!
How was that?
It's called "Tossing up bales."
What's in the bales?
Dirt. Heavier than rice.
So how much will Lord Uesugi pay for me?
OISHI'S HOME IN YAMASHINA
Kichiemon!
Mother! Kichiemon Terasaka's here.
You're a big boy now.
I'm very glad you've come.
We have few visitors since moving here; the children miss company.
I'm sorry. I meant to come sooner.
